<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-26T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-26T16:00:00-05:00" n="350" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d350">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/344</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MCK1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Moser</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-26T16:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">March 26,
                                            1918, 4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>For <persName corresp="#p_SJF1">Stevens</persName>:</p>
                            <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">Francis</persName> has asked
                                you to send six units of Railway Service Corps to European Russia.
                                Take no action at present. What progress are you making at Harbin?
                                Are any of the men still at Nagasaki? Glad you are continuing
                                efforts.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_LR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>